WEBVTT

00:00.031 --> 00:01.033
All right, let's dive in.

00:01.093 --> 00:05.402
So vision transformers are a new thing, right?

00:05.843 --> 00:07.005
Vision transformers.

00:07.546 --> 00:11.113
I've also made a video about vision transformers.

00:11.514 --> 00:18.748
They are the easy, the simple application of the transformer architecture, which was

00:18.728 --> 00:28.082
prevalent in natural language processing with the introduction of attention is all you need and follow up papers, BERT and so on.

00:28.863 --> 00:32.308
And applying this to images.

00:32.769 --> 00:34.431
And the concept is very simple.

00:35.293 --> 00:38.117
You have an image and you divide this into patches.

00:38.598 --> 00:40.821
So you divide the image into patches.

00:42.404 --> 00:45.831
And then you simply unroll that array sort of.

00:45.951 --> 00:47.374
So you unroll that array.

00:47.394 --> 00:51.483
So you have patch, patch, patch, patch, and so on.

00:52.304 --> 01:01.864
And then you simply consider this as a sequence, like a sentence, like, Hello, my name is, and so on.

01:01.844 --> 01:06.633
you simply consider the sequence of patches as word embeddings.

01:06.994 --> 01:14.848
So there's like one, I think there is one fully connected layer to actually get the word embedding or the token embedding.

01:15.229 --> 01:20.659
And then you put a transformer as you would in an LP.

01:20.679 --> 01:23.785
So there is a transformer

01:24.710 --> 01:24.990
here.

01:25.972 --> 01:28.957
And you do whatever you do with a transformer.

01:29.137 --> 01:42.820
So usually, if you don't know, people prepend a special token, that special token is usually called something where I might not draw this, that special token is usually called CLS token.

01:42.800 --> 01:49.229
And that is also passed through the transformer and the transformer in its base configuration.

01:50.852 --> 01:53.616
It keeps the length of the sequence the same.

01:53.716 --> 01:57.722
It's actually not necessary to do this, but that's just how we do things.

01:58.503 --> 02:07.997
So for every input token, you'll get a corresponding output token or output embedding or output signal, whatever you want to call it.

02:07.977 --> 02:20.517
And such that none of the input tokens is, you know, kind of preferred because every input token sort of refers to some little patch here in the image.

02:21.538 --> 02:26.165
If you want to say something about the entire image, you don't want to prefer any one of them.

02:26.586 --> 02:30.492
So what you do is you have this special token, the CLS token.

02:30.472 --> 02:33.476
which is associated with no location in the image.

02:33.496 --> 02:41.486
And that's ultimately what you use to classify the image or also here to do representation learning.

02:41.546 --> 02:49.336
So the representation we're looking to get out is the final layer embedding of the CLS token.

02:49.816 --> 02:59.989
And that through the transformer architecture had aggregated all the information or we hope so from all the visual tokens in the image.

